@simonedelmann inline should overwrite `defaultValues` at the `useForm`. This is applied to `useFieldArray` as well, v7.8.0 is the correct behaviour to avoid default value conflict.

```tsx
import React from "react";
import { useForm, useFieldArray } from "react-hook-form";

function App() {
  const { register, control, handleSubmit, reset, trigger, setError } = useForm({
    defaultValues: {
      test: [{ lastName: 'test' }]
    };
  });
  const { fields, append, prepend, remove, swap, move, insert } = useFieldArray({
    control,
    name: "test"
  });
  
  return (
    <form onSubmit={handleSubmit(data => console.log(data))}>
      <ul>
        {fields.map((item, index) => (
          <li key={item.id}>
            <Controller
              render={({ field }) => <input {...field} />}
              name={`test.${index}.lastName`}
              control={control}
              defaultValue={item.lastName} // inline defaultValue is taking over defaultValues.
            />
            <button type="button" onClick={() => remove(index)}>Delete</button>
          </li>
        ))}
      </ul>
      <button
        type="button"
        onClick={() => append({ firstName: "appendBill", lastName: "appendLuo" })}
      >
        append
      </button>
      <input type="submit" />
    </form>
  );
}
```

@bluebill1049 Thanks for your answer! I would strongly prefer `defaultValues` to override `defaultValue` also for controlled inputs. Otherwise it wouldn't be possible anymore to throw an existing object (e.g. from database) in `defaultValues` and have the whole form state correct. Also I would prefer controlled and uncontrolled inputs to behave as similar as possible. 
Is there maybe a way to add a flag for that?

